Author: Tom Holt

Author: Matt Stoller

Title: Blood Meridian, or, the Evening Redness in the West
Author: Cormac McCarthy

Title: Deconstructing Penguins: Parents, Kids, and the Bond of Reading
Author: Lawrence Goldstone
My Review: This book is a pretty alright book to read. It’s not too difficult to understand and it gives a good foundation for talking through books and their deeper meanings with children through the use of examples of real discussions. If you’re teaching children critical thinking and looking deeper at books, this could be a book to read, among other books.

Title: Purple and Black
Author: K.J. Parker
My Review: 4.3/5 - I thought this was a pretty good book, leaving a good bit of stuff to chew on at the end, concerning governance and practice/thought. This novella is done in a bit of a unique format, with the letters and such, which is still able to lend itself to a quite nice narrative. Overall, I thought this was a pretty good book, all things considered.

Title: The Management Style of the Supreme Beings
Author: Tom Holt

Title: Unlocked: An Oral History of Haden's Syndrome (Lock In, #0.5)
Author: John Scalzi

Title: The Android's Dream
Author: John Scalzi
My Review: I have thoroughly enjoyed reading this book. I especially liked the way all of the different plot threads were woven together with the different actors in the book culminating in an immensely satisfying conclusion. I would recommend reading this book as it is a greatly fun read.

Title: Miniatures: The Very Short Fiction of John Scalzi
Author: John Scalzi

Title: Lovelock (Mayflower Trilogy, #1)
Author: Orson Scott Card
My Review: This is a pretty interesting read about a genetically modified monkey made to be a helper for a future scientist, along with some of the implications of this, as told from the monkey’s point of view. I enjoyed some of the questions that it raised in my mind as I read the narrative, and felt this novel was quite a good work by Card and Kidd. There’s a good amount of social dynamics between the characters, and it’s a touch light on the sci-fi stuff, but I felt that it is a great read nonetheless.

Title: How to Keep House While Drowning
Author: K.C.  Davis

Title: The Art Thief: A True Story of Love, Crime, and a Dangerous Obsession
Author: Michael Finkel

Title: I Who Have Never Known Men
Author: Jacqueline Harpman

Title: This Is How You Lose the Time War
Author: Amal El-Mohtar

Title: Before the Coffee Gets Cold (Before the Coffee Gets Cold, #1)
Author: Toshikazu Kawaguchi

Title: An Immense World: How Animal Senses Reveal the Hidden Realms Around Us
Author: Ed Yong

Author: Tim Alberta

Author: Bryan Chapell

Title: Days at the Morisaki Bookshop (Days at the Morisaki Bookshop, #1)
Author: Satoshi Yagisawa

Title: The Last Theorem
Author: Arthur C. Clarke
My Review: The narrative is pretty well written, but towards the end there seemed to be an increasing amount of sort of anti-religion stuff that was quite out of place and I was not a fan of. But, overall I thought it was a pretty good book.

Title: Fuzzy Nation (Fuzzy Sapiens, #7)
Author: John Scalzi
My Review: A really enjoyable read that I accidentally finished in one day. It has a really great and intriguing plot and was hard to put down. If you like a light sci-fi novel about an alien species, mega-corporation vs the little guy, and a good story, you’re sure to enjoy this book. Would recommend.

Title: The End of All Things (Old Man's War, #6)
Author: John Scalzi

Title: Too Much to Know: Managing Scholarly Information before the Modern Age
Author: Ann M. Blair

Title: Dreaming in Code: Two Dozen Programmers, Three Years, 4,732 Bugs, and One Quest for Transcendent Software
Author: Scott Rosenberg

Title: Data-ism: The Revolution Transforming Decision Making, Consumer Behavior, and Almost Everything Else
Author: Steve Lohr

Title: When Gadgets Betray Us: The Dark Side of Our Infatuation With New Technologies
Author: Robert Vamosi

Title: The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited
Author: Louisa Lim
My Review: An interesting book that brings to light what happened in Tienanmen Square 1989 as well as a chapter touching on another connected tragedy that has been covered up by the CCP. I liked that she based her information off of other people and included the way that their lives have been impacted by that event.

Title: Algorithms to Live By: The Computer Science of Human Decisions
Author: Brian Christian

Title: As Gods Among Men: A History of the Rich in the West
Author: Guido   Alfani

Title: Sunstorm (A Time Odyssey, #2)
Author: Arthur C. Clarke
My Review: Another great book from Clarke and Baxter, 4.5 stars. A really enjoyable book about a disaster involving the sun. I found it very interesting, and enjoyed the narrative, although some of the scientific explanations were a bit complicated for my puny mind to fully comprehend. Overall, would recommend reading this book, which is related to the first book in the series, but mostly stands on its own as a part of the overarching narrative of the Time Odyssey series, which I hope to finish reading soon.

Title: Childhood’s End
Author: Arthur C. Clarke
My Review: A truly fascinating book that I strongly recommend reading. It provides a quite interesting and captivating narrative, which I readily devoured. Truly masterful.

Title: Time's Eye (A Time Odyssey, #1)
Author: Arthur C. Clarke
My Review: Really interesting book about what might happen if the world was carved up through time by the “Discontinuity”. I found the narrative thrilling and very intriguing, and quickly read the whole book. I’m looking forward to reading the next books in this series and always appreciate the books produced by the collaboration between these two great authors.

Title: 12 Ways Your Phone Is Changing You
Author: Tony Reinke

Title: God, Technology, and the Christian Life
Author: Tony Reinke

Title: Hidden in Plain View: A Secret Story of Quilts and the Underground Railroad
Author: Jacqueline L. Tobin
Additional Authors: Raymond G. Dobard, Maude S. Wahlman

Title: Computer Science: Discovering God's Glory in Ones and Zeros
Author: Jonathan R. Stoddard

Title: The Light of Other Days
Author: Arthur C. Clarke
My Review: A really fascinating book about the invention of this technology and the implications that it would have for the species told through a compelling narrative. While not entirely realistic and at times showing the authors’ viewpoints, I found it interesting and worth a read.

Title: Liturgy of the Ordinary: Sacred Practices in Everyday Life
Author: Tish Harrison Warren
My Review: This book explores and considers some fascinating ideas about connecting one’s daily moments and practices to the worship of God. I found it useful and engaging, and would recommend it for the considerations it presents.

Title: Shaping a Digital World: Faith, Culture and Computer Technology
Author: Derek C. Schuurman
My Review: I found this book really fascinating, even as I had to read it for school. It frames technology and its developments and consequences in a good way, showing how there latent possibilities in creation for technology and then how it’s used with creational norms and all of that. Also, it takes a lot from other places like Scripture and other authors in the field, such as Frederick Brooks and some of his books, among others. Overall, this book is very well done and was quite well researched, and encouraged me to consider diving into this topic a bit further on my own with its excellent bibliography.

Title: How It Went: Thirteen More Stories of the Port William Membership
Author: Wendell Berry

Title: Prey
Author: Michael Crichton
My Review: More fantastic work from Michael Crichton! He does an excellent job of exploring through this story a fascinating topic, and I also loved the little bit of cynicism towards corporations hehe. Overall, great read, would recommend! Exhilarating to the finish!

Title: Stolen Focus: Why You Can't Pay Attention--and How to Think Deeply Again
Author: Johann Hari

Title: You've Been Played: How Corporations, Governments, and Schools Use Games to Control Us All
Author: Adrian Hon
My Review: Really interesting book. Explained a lot about the different ways in which gamification is used in our society, whether in schools, government, lifestyle, work, and even online conspiracy theories. It was fascinating seeing the ways in which gamification is used to coerce behavior and how that is not proven to be very effective. While I wasn’t quite in agreement on every thing he said, overall it was an enjoyable read.

Title: Dirk Gently's Holistic Detective Agency (Dirk Gently, #1)
Author: Douglas Adams

Title: Confronting Christianity: 12 Hard Questions for the World's Largest Religion
Author: Rebecca McLaughlin

Title: The Cathedral & the Bazaar: Musings on Linux and Open Source by an Accidental Revolutionary
Author: Eric S. Raymond

Title: The Foundation Trilogy (Foundation, #1-3)
Author: Isaac Asimov
My Review: Amazing book, lots of great twists and intrigue. Really neat how it goes through some of the history of the Foundation through the eyes of different people in it. Will definitely be reading the some of the other books in the series next.

Title: The Mythical Man-Month: Essays on Software Engineering
Author: Frederick P. Brooks Jr.

Title: Why I Am Not Going to Buy a Computer
Author: Wendell Berry

Title: The Shallows: What the Internet Is Doing to Our Brains
Author: Nicholas Carr

Title: Cutting Back: My Apprenticeship in the Gardens of Kyoto
Author: Leslie Buck

Title: Stolen Focus: Why You Can't Pay Attention— and How to Think Deeply Again
Author: Johann Hari

Title: When You Lie About Your Age, the Terrorists Win: Reflections on Looking in the Mirror
Author: Carol Leifer
My Review: This book is pretty alright. It’s fascinating to see things from such a different perspective from my own, and although I certainly don’t agree with all of it, it’s still good to see the world through the lens of someone who’s lived so much of it. It’s a somewhat short read, so it’s a good way to fill an afternoon.

Title: Upgrade
Author: Blake Crouch
My Review: This book is extremely engrossing. I really like the premise of the book with gene editing, especially since it seems like something that could very well happen in the next century. The narrative really draws you in and keeps you hanging on every word. I look forward to reading other books by this author and wholeheartedly recommend this book to anyone looking for a good read.

Title: Life and Death Are Wearing Me Out
Author: Mo Yan

Title: Clone: The Road to Dolly and the Path Ahead
Author: Gina Kolata
My Review: I really enjoyed reading this book. It was a fascinating look at the history of cloning and some of the debates around the ethics and implications of cloning. I don’t really read much fiction, but I found this book at a thrift store and decided to read it and am glad that I did. I think I’ll be reading much more nonfiction in the future, as this helped me in developing my opinions on cloning and genetic engineering of humans and animals. While it was written some time ago, it’s still quite relevant today and is fascinating when considering the advances we have made in cloning since this book released.

Title: Ring (Xeelee Sequence, #4)
Author: Stephen Baxter
My Review: This is probably one of the first books that I’ve read just by Stephen Baxter (I have read the Long Earth series), and it was really great. The world it paints is so rich and the story is fascinating. When I started on this book, I was unaware it was part of a series, but it stands on its own. I’m sure if I read the other books in the series I’d be more informed of some of the parts, but it stands well on its own. Overall, I really enjoyed this book and cannot wait to read some of the other books of his in the future.

Author: Orson Scott Card
